|><| 𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐢𝐧 𝐉𝐚𝐯𝐚 |><|
      >> Strings in Java are objects that represent a sequence of characters.
      >> They are one of the most commonly used data types and provide a wide range of features for manipulating text. 

  >> All literal in java programs , such as "abc" are implemented as instance of class.

        String s = "abc";
        print(s);

-------------------><-----------------------><----------------------

|><| 𝐒𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐏𝐨𝐨𝐥 |><|
      >> The string pool is the area in Heap memory where String literal are stored.

    String s1 = "abc"  \
    String s2 = "abc"   \ _____  
    String s3 = "def"   /"""""" >>>> Inside String Pool
         s2 = "hello"  /

   Using New keyword in String Pool
       String s1 = "abc"
       String s2 = new String("abc")     --->> Outside String Pool

𝚆𝚛𝚒𝚝𝚝𝚎𝚗 𝚖𝚎𝚝𝚑𝚘𝚍 𝚒𝚜 𝚜𝚊𝚖𝚎 𝚋𝚞𝚝 𝚋𝚘𝚝𝚑 𝚊𝚛𝚎 𝚍𝚒𝚏𝚏𝚎𝚛𝚎𝚗𝚝-𝚍𝚒𝚏𝚏𝚎𝚛𝚎𝚗𝚝 𝚒𝚗 𝚂𝚝𝚛𝚒𝚗𝚐 𝚙𝚘𝚘𝚕.

    s1.equals(s2)  --> This method make the same string pool.

